{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2goncharova_ver03/data/sn83045462/00280605244/1949010201/0080.xml":{"full_text":"Business and Financial Review\nEducational\nffyc fhtnflay gtaf\nClassified Ads\nPages 11 to 17\nEIGHTEEN PAGES\nWASHINGTON, D. JANUARY 2, 1949\nRecord Activity of 1948 Shows Signs of Leveling Off at Year's End\n1948 One of Best\nYears on Record,\nD.C. Bankers Say\nFace Increasing Costs\nAnd Taxes, but Loans\nHold at High Levels\nBy Edward C. Stone\nWashington bank officials say\n1948 was one of their best years on\nrecord, with loans near the highest\npoint yet reached, deposits around\npeak levels, and\nearnings suffi\ncient for regu\nlar dividends\nand many ex\ntras. Annual re\nports will prove\ne x c e p t i onally\ngood reading.\nHowever, bank\ning institutions!\nare still bat-'\ntling rising op\nerating costs,\nstruggling with\ntaxes and many\nother problems.\nThey are unable\nEdw. C. Stone.\nto pay high enough interest to at\ntract savings in growing amounts.\nTightening of credit to help the\nTreasury check inflation limited\nloan volume in the last half year, j\nThe city's building and loan as-'\nsociations saw total assets enter\nnew ground, again placed huge sums\nin home loans to veterans and\nregistered a marked increase in the\nnumber of new shareholders, an\nimpressive 12 months.\nBank clearings, one of the lead\ning indicators of general business,\nsmashed all previous marks in 1948\nwith a total for 12 months of\n$3,661,078,549, a jump of $234,456,490\nabove 1947.\nExchange Volume Jumps.\nTrading expansion on the Wash\nington Stock Exchange proved sen\nsational, due* to the adoption of\nfive-hour sessions at the urgent1\nsuggestion of Bernard J. Nees, presi\ndent. and to the exceptional appeal\nof leading issues on the board. Other\ninvestment developments included\nthe opening of branch brokerage,\nbffices in Silver Spring and\nBethesda.\nDeptarment store sales, including,\nChristmas trade, were 5 per cent;\nahead of the peak year 1947, auto-,\nmobile sales far exceeded the pre\nceding 12 months; gas and electri-j\ncity sales were up; telephones in j\nservice and daily calls entered new,\nground. Fostai receipts climbed\nsteadily.\nLife insurance policies totaling j\n$117,627,000 in 11 months were 2 per- j\ncent under the 1947 figures. Rising;\ncosts curbed atility eawungs, but'\nhigher rates gave relief in a year\nof exceptional expansion.\nFinanciers looking ahead to 19491\nsee many readjustments due, but\nevince little worry over the District\u2019s j\nbusiness outlook because of the j\nstable Government payroll, which\nmakes Washington a most favored\ncity.\nLeaders Review Year.\nThe 27 associations comprising\nthe District of Columbia Building\nand Loan League loaned approxi\nmately $115,000,000 for home con\nst ruction during\n1948, compared\nwith $124,732,000\nin 1947, Edward\nL. McAleer, pres\nident, announc\ned.\nDuring the war\nand a year\nafterward scar\ncity of building\nmaterials made\nthe construction\nof homes prac\ntically impossi\nble. But in 1947\nand to a greater\nextent in 1948\nE. L. McAleer.\nsupplies began to arrive in such\nquantities that builders in this area\nwere able to break all records in\nsupplying sorely needed homes.\nThese building associations now\nhave 50,000 borrowing members,\nmore than 165,000 savings members\nwhile assets exceed $350,000,000.\nThey made 40 percent of the loans\nfor home purchases in this area in\n1948.\nBest Record in 20 Years.\nMore shares of stock changed\nhands on the Washington Stock\nExchange during 1948 than at any\ntime in the last 20 years, Bernard J.\nNees, president,\nstated. The in\ncreased volume\nreflected greater\ninterest by\nWashington in\nvestors in local\nissues and the\nexpanded facili\nties of the Ex\nchange, trading\nhours now par\nalleling those of\nthe New York\nmarkets.\nUtility stocks\nare in larger\nsupply as the\nB. J. Nee*.\nresult of the dissolution of holding\ncompanies and new financing.\nLower prices also have made yields\n(Continued on Page E-7, Col. 3.)\nAmerican Newspapers\nSet Records in 1948\nBy the Associated Press\nNEW YORK, Jan. 1.\u2014Editor\nPublisher predicts a prosperous 1949\nfor American newspapers.\nIn its January 1 issue, the pub\nlishers and advertisers\u2019 weekly says\nadvertising linage, barring unex\npected^evelopments, should surpass\n1948\u2019s record total; circulation will\nremain at a high level; more news\nprint will be available, and new\nequipment will be easier to get.\nOn the debit side, it said news\npaper production costs rose to a new\nhigh in 1948 and may go even higher\nin 1949.\nTerming 1948 the best year in the\nhistory of newspaper advertising, the\nweekly said the dollar volume prob\nably would reach $434,000,000, com\npared to $357,000,000 in 1947. And\n1949 ahould be better.\nr\u2014i\u2014J-1 I I T \u25a0'!1\njgggjgg i g \u00bbT?iBtlT ttM \u00bbTiTf\u00bblTFWiT^^\u00a3TrfftPM stocks and commodities\njMBBaaafa gj 888tos.\u00ab\u00abr\u00ab x A S 9 jagg 8' A\u201c a A jB k r\u00bb Jwwftao a S Jf I m a 18&\u00a3& ia\nI^W^wfcWA 1 Bftl. Y/ |tT, yal fa b-^ ^aS \"qgT **^88888\n\"Mf k i iki k*J \u201cJ p p t^S k\u2122 m\nI commodity ho\n\u201c\u25bc\u2019T\"\u201d-'-oaooaaBaooaeoooooooBooooooooooooooeoooeoowosoBOOWoeoooooooBOOWOWOOOOOOWOOOoooo^ocwoooowoooooooooooeooowooooww m\nV STOCK\nI I T\nHOUSE PASSES DRAFT, I\nFOREIGN AIO BUIS J\n2^ 2 2 Cft.. ts I 1 \"|9J9 40 '41 -42 '43 '44 '*i *46 '47 4\u00ab\nf T\u00bb/ I- 4 i. 9*\\_\nm\u00ab in I DEWEY I TRUMAN\n200 /U f ELECTED\n195 (9 ^--1\ni\n<m c r. REDS BOYCOTT\nI3Q 0 0 ---f4-1 BERLIN ELECTION\n185 6 4\nm 62 ma7^IScommod.t.es' ~l;^r-lTAX 'tD[iC\"\u00b0\" IIU^ COMMODITY PRICES ~~1~\n(Associated Press index of 35 weighted\nI*commodities; Base Year 1926 equals IOO)\n175 60 ---^-1-\u2014|-f-1\nIAN. FEB. MAR. APR. MAY JUN. JUL. AUG. SEP. OCT. NOV. DEC.\nE2\nSALES ON N. Y. STOCK EXCHANGE IN 1948\nTOTAL STOCK SALES.\nBy the Associated Press.\nTotal 1948, revised.-. 302,218.965\nTotal 1947 253.623