-Hay W A 1% 493 264* 20% 20%\u2014 3%\nKclsey-Hay W B 1% 888 22% 154, 16%\u2014 4%\nKennecott Cop 5e 10,593 60% 42% 55%+ 6%\nKern C Land 3a <_ 1.102 51 404. 43%\nKeystone SAW 1 217 16% 12% 134.\nXimber-Clark 1.40a 1.763 24 19 20%\u2014 1\nxKimb-Clark pf 4 10.41(1 104% 02 04%\u2014 8%\nKinney (G R) la 135 14% 11% 12 1%\nxKinney pf 3 3,780 75 03 05 7%\nKoppers Co 2 1,412 37% 29% 29%\u2014 6%\nxKoppers Co pf 4 7,080 95% 80 91\nKresge <S S) 2a _ 1,599 3St% 32 38\nKress (S H) 2a 704 58% 45% 54%+ 5%\nKroger Co 3e 780 40 40% 43 3%\nLaclede Gas .20 5,512 0% 4% 5\nLa Consolid pf ,73e 340 12 4% 4%\u2014.4%\nLambert Co 1% 1,081 24 17 17%\u2014 4\nLane Bryant 1 707 14% 9% 10\nxLane Bry pf 2% 3,220 53% 42 43%\u2014 6%\nLane-Wells 2.20e\u2014 702 30% 20% 25%\nLee Rub Tire 2a_. 340 47 35 37 6%\nLees Sons 1.40a 422 20% 21% 22%\u2014 3%\nxLees Sons pf 3.85 800 99 90 90%\u2014 6\nLehigh C N 1_ 2,068 13% 10 10%+\nLehigh Port C 2a\u2014 1.075 39 30% 37%+ 1\nLehigh Val Coal_ 7,041 4% 1% 2%+\nLeh V Coal 1 pf 3\u2014 1,205 26% 19% 22%+ 3\nLeh V Coal 2 pf 1,003 10% 5% 7%+ 1%\nLeh Val R R _ 2,559 8% 4% 4%\u2014\nLehman Corp 3%e\u2014 1.993 50 41% 45 4\nLehn Fink %e_ 040 12 8% 8%\u2014 2%\nLerner Stores 2 1,408 20% 10% 20%+ 3%\nLib-O-F Glass 3 %e 2,251 50% 43% 45%\u2014 9%\nLibby, McN L %e. 4.278 10% 8 8%\u2014 1%\nLife Savers 2%e 392 38% 31% 35%\u2014 2%\nLlgget Myers 4a 1,303 91 82 80%\u2014 1%\nxLiggett My pf 7. 8,0HO 174% 157 170 2\nLily-Tulip 2 204 47 33 38 2\nLlma-Hamil ,03e_ 0.437 13% 8% 9%\u2014\nLink-Belt 4a _ 055 70% 55% 04%+ 1%\nLion Oil 3 2,827 55% 28% 41%+ 7%\nLiquid Carbonic lb 1.358 23% 15',. io%\u2014 5%\nLiquid Carb pf 3%e. 125 85 08% 75 Va\u2014 3\nLockheed Alrc l%e _ 7.543 25% 13% 16%+ 3%\nLoew s Inc 1% 1,341 20% 14Via 14%\u2014 4%\nLone Star Cem 3%a. 1,309 08% 57% 65 2\nLong-Bell Lbr A 4k. 1,209 30% 18 20 6%\nLorillard P la. _. 2.117 21% 18 19%+\nxLorlllard P pf 7 55 158 138 153V.+ 13%\nLouisv G E 1.60. 119 25 23 23%\nLouis Nash 3.52.. 2.000 50 37 38%\u2014 6%\nLowenstein 2a _ 2.057 35% 20 22%\u2014 3%\n(Continued on Page E-2.)\nDogged by Fear,!\nStocks Ignored\nU. S. Prosperity\nBy William D. Horgan\n(Associated Press Market Writer.) i\nNEW YORK, Jan. 1.\u2014The stock\nmarket distinguished itself in 1948\nby ignoring the Nation\u2019s most pros\nperous year.\nIt was a year in which fears and\nuncertainties tumbled out of the\nheadlines with scarcely an inter\nruption. The cold war between1\ncapitalism and communism, peace\nscares and war scares, inflation,\nfourth-round wage increases, tax:\nprospects\u2014these and other factors\ndogged the heels of the market\nthrough the year.\nIt was a year of several violent,\nfluctuations and weeks of stagna\ntion.\nIt was the latest stretch in one\nof the longest sidewise price move\nments in the history cf the modern\nstock market.\nAt the start of 1948 the Asso\nciated Press average of 60 stocks:\nstood at $65.70 a share. Today the\nmarket closed with the average at\n$64.50.\nThe classical theory that cor\nporation earnings are in the long\nrun the .determining factor in stock\nprices w;as all but thrown over\nboard.\nRecord Profits Cited.\nCorporation profits in 1948 were\nthe highest on record, as they had\nbeen in turn, in 1947 and in 1946.\nThe answer to stock price fluctua\ntions\u2014if there is any single answer\n\u2014lies elsewhere.\nThe stock market is afraid of its\nown shadow. The market sees\ndanger in every rumor, peril in\nevery threat, a menace in every\nheadline.\nThe market lives in a world of\nbogeys and the bogey population in\nWall Street increased at an alarm\ning rate in 1948.\nThe stability of the market may\nbe considered impressive if we\nmeasure price trends in terms of\ndoubt and uncertainty. A rich busi\nness record, in other words, pro\nvided a solid foundation for a mar\nket that otherwise would have top\npled under the weight of its own\nfears.\nIn February the price level, as\nmeasured by the AP 60-stock aver\nage, reached the low for the year.\nA slow, arduous advance got under\nway which reached a relatively\ndizzy climax in mid-May.\nHelping demand were the domestic\nrearmament and the European aid\nprograms, both of which were re\ngarded as substantial contributions\nagainst the possibility of a recession.\nRise Started in May.\nIn mid-May a buying drive hit the\nmarket with all the power of a Mis\nsouri mule kick. In the broadest\nmarket on record up to that time,\nnearly 4.000,000 shares of stock\nchanged hands, an eight-year high.\nThe reason for a sudden national\nurge to buy stocks was as simple as\nit was curious: The industrial stock\naverage passed a so-called \u201cresist\nance point\" and unleashed buying\npower that astounded Wall Street.\nA bull market was on the move,\naccording to enthusiastic reports\nfrom downtown Manhattan. The\nreports turned out to be a bum steer.\nRussian-United States relations\nover Berlin went from one crisis, to\nanother. The bull market managed\nto put on a pound or two of weight\nuntil early July when the high of\nthe year was established\u2014$72.40 by\nthe AP average.\nIn mid-July the bull move curled\nup its toes and called it a day.\nPrices dropped like a chunk of lead\nin water. What happened? The\nBerlin blockade argument had\nreached the stage where people were\ntalking of war. The President called\na special session of Congress. United\nStates Steel Corp., bellwether of\nAmerican industry, announced a\nwage-price increase. Overnight\n(See HORGAN. Page E-2.)\nMany Firms Face\nSmaller Profits\nAs Sales Decline\nAdjustment Expected,\nBut Authorities Hope\nIt Can Be Controlled\nBy Harry T. Montgomery\nAssociated Press General Business Editor\nNEW YORK, Jan, 1.\u2014The postwar\nboom carried the United States\nthrough a record-breaking prosper\nity in 1948, but appeared to be level\nlmg off at year\nend.\nMost forecas\nters saw\u2019 con\ntinued good\ntimes for the\nmonths ahead,\nalthough some\nof the business\ncommunity ap\nproached 1949\nwith apprehen\nsion.\nProfit margins\nW\u2019ere narrowing\nin many lines,\nand other weak\npoints were be\nH. T. Montgomery.\nginning to show up. Retail sales,\nalthough high by \u201cnormal-\u2019 stand\nards. slowed up in the final month*\nof 1948. Many business leaders ex\npressed concern over what 1949\nwould bring in Government control*\nand taxes.\nMany of the records set in 1948\nw'ere in dollar figures, reflecting in\nflation. In the final months of the\nyear the rate of increase generally\nwas declining. It seemed that 1948\nwould eventually be recorded as the\npeak of the boom. Among the\nsmaller industries, where a reversal\ntraditionally shows up first, a pinch\nalready was being felt at year end,\nControl is Problem.\nOur problem is to control the ad\njustment apparently being made: te\nachieve a level of prosperity, prob\nably below- that of 1948, and avoid\na recession or depression. Top\nauthorities feel a sharp setback can\nbe avoided, and that we have many\nmonths ahead of \u201cgood times.\u201d\nThe country as a whole was riding\nthe highest and longest postwar\nboom in history as 1948 ended. With\nmost of the rest of the world still\nstaggering from the wreck of war,\nI the United States was sailing along\nat a clip undreamed of only a few\nyears ago.\nThe averagl citizen felt the pros\ni perity in the highest standard of\nliving the world has ever known,\nj Prices were high\u2014they hit records\nalong with almost everything else\u2014\nbut incomes also were high, and the\npeople were using more automobiles\nand more home appliances, and W\u2019ere\nI better clothed and better fed than\never before.\nSome Groups Pinched.\nIn the midst of this general pros\nperity, some groups have been\npinched by inflation. People with\nfixed incomes, some white collar\nworkers and salaried professional and\n.semiprofessional employes have been\namong those not faring so well. And\nthe lower income man, regardless of\nhis occupation, found it harder to\nmake ends meet under the high cost\nof food.\nThe economist, who studies the\nboom in figures, had only record\nhighs to look at in surveying 1948.\nThe value of what the country\nproduces (gross national product)\nhad soared to a record annual rate\nof $256,000,000,000 in the closing\nmonths of the year. The rate was at\n$243,800,000,000 at the end of 1947,\nand was $229,608,000,000 for the\nwhole of 1947.\nThe people's total earnings, in\ncluding profits and wages (national\nj income) hit-a rate of around $225,\n000,000,000, against a rate of $212,\ni (See MONTGOMERY, Page E-9.f*\nANNUAL FORECAST\nFOR 1949\nv\nRECOMMENDS A LIST OF ATTRACTIVE LOW PRICED STOCKS\nAND INDICATES MARKET OPINION OF OTHER\nACTIVE LISTED STOCKS\nFREE COPY ON REQUEST (CALL OR WRITE)\nRobert C. Jones Co.\nMembers New York and Washington Stock\nExchanges\n613 Fifteenth Street N.W. ME. 2922\nOther Office!\n1713 Eye Street N.W.\nGround Floor\nME. 2922\nSerimgeour Building\nSilver Spring, Md.\nSH. 5452\nComplete Investment Service at 3 Convenient Locations\nREAD THIS BOOKLET\nieW'0* H\ni ft***\"*\n\"Solving Your Investment Problems\u201d\nShows how you can obtain wise diversifi\ncation, expert supervision. Written and\nplanned for easy reading by America\u2019s\nforemost authority on Investment Com\npanies. Points out how you can reduce\nyour risks, improve dependability of\ninvestment income.\nRead this booklet now\u2014without cost\nor obligation. Write or phone for your\ncopy today.\nFERRIS COMPANY\nMembers New York Washinoton Stock txchanoes\nMAIN OFFICE\n523 WASH. BLDG.\nST. 5924\nBRANCH OFFICE\n7006 WISCONSIN AVE.\nOL. 4172 WH. 0285","height":"31648","width":"22420"}}
